title: do not check the frame of dMonitorState  if frontview is false
Haotic gas/brake comands Toyota Highlander 2019 -master-ci
body:
**Describe the bug**

When stopped in trafic the OP seems to have chaotic distance measurements from the stopped car in front, these leads to chaotic brake system engagements and disengaments which can be seen from specific noise of brake system, car micro movements, headlights darkening (from the power consumption of brake fluid pump)

**How to reproduce or log data**

Stop in traffic with OP engaged

**Expected behavior**

Some "smoothing" of distance data or gas/brake commands needed in the near zero speed modes.


**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: comma two
 - Dongle ID: 922bcfdc7c1e117d
 - Route: [e.g. 922bcfdc7c1e117d|2020-12-21--5:10PM - 5:29PM
 - Timestamp: -11minute-13second
 - Version: master-ci 12/21/2020
 - Car make/model: Toyota Highlander 2019 safety sense, derated to 249 hp

**Additional context**

Also at speed around 60 kmph with 8 mode automatic transmission same reason of unsmoothed gas commands lead to chaotic change of switching between 6,7,8 transmission mode (since the car cant understand if you are moving steadily in eco mode or trying to accelerate). Also some smoothing required.

title: UI: add function ui_read_params
body:
Read all paramaters in  `ui_read_params()`.

because `frame` starts from 0, all parameters will be read at the first time call of `ui_read_params()`. so we don’t need to read them in `ui_init`.

title: Add speed limit indicator
body:
Made a new service `speedlimitd` that uses gps long/lat from `gpsLocationExternal`, looks up the recent road segments in Mapbox's map matching API, and publishes `liveMapData`, which is previously unused as far as I can tell.

Here's a showcase of it from a drive earlier this evening: https://youtube.com/watch?v=GkIRIIrR5ik

The biggest downside of the feature is that right now, it needs a Mapbox access token to work (located at a new path `/persist/mapbox/access_token`). So either each person wanting to use the feature needs to get their own Mapbox account and access token, or it could be a comma prime feature where y'all could expose a new endpoint backed by Mapbox.

This branch also includes a couple other minor fixes/improvements

Looking forward to the feedback!

title: Toyota: don't cut steering for 2 seconds after fault recovery
body:
When a fault occurs, LKA_STATE is 25 on rising edge, then 9 for ~200 frames. Since the code in carcontroller kept resetting the `last_fault_frame` variable, it only started the 2 second timer once the fault was over and steering was possible. Now instead it will start steering immediately after state returns to normal, so 4 seconds to 2 seconds of loss of control after a fault.

You can see here that after the first 2 seconds, the state is 1 (not applying torque but ready) for another 2 seconds when we could be steering again. I'm wondering if this breaks anything for other Toyotas, though It worked perfectly for my 17 Corolla.

![Screenshot_137](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25857203/102369853-08bf8680-3f82-11eb-9b0d-a9d94e18a880.png)

title: Openpilot calibration stuck at 0% [Comma 2 / 2018 RAV4]
body:
**Describe the bug**

I purchased the comma 2 for my 2018 rav4 xle about 1 month ago. I am having issues getting it to calibrate. What is happening is that I will get the screen that says 'calibration 0% drive above 15mph' and then nothing happens. No errors and no changes in percent even after driving for 1hr. I have tried versions 0.7.9, 0.7.10, and 0.8.0 with community features both enabled and disabled for each version and I get the same results. I have tried unplugging everything and re-plugging. I've looked through the logs and it looks like almost everything under 'liveCalibration' is zero and does not update. The community says that the mounting looks good from the photos and dashcam recording I posted to discord. 

**How to reproduce or log data**

1. Start the car
2. Wait for calibration screen to display
3. Drive for a while but no change in percent or errors

Log Data: all 'liveCalibration' blocks appear to have the same values seen below.

> ( logMonoTime = 11086766343778,
  liveCalibration = (
    calStatus = 0,
    calCycle = 0,
    calPerc = 0,
    extrinsicMatrix = [0, -1, 0, 0, 0, 0, -1, 1.22, 1, 0, 0, 0],
    rpyCalib = [0, 0, 0],
    rpyCalibSpread = [0, 0, 0],
    validBlocks = 0 ),
  valid = true )


**Expected behavior**

I expect it to calibrate or display an error that it can not calibrate. 

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: Comma 2
 - Dongle ID: 0feb5791ebfe2272
 - Route:  0feb5791ebfe2272|2020-12-09--17-11-23 [0.8.0], 	0feb5791ebfe2272|2020-11-06--15-40-51[0.7.9]
 - Timestamp: Entire drive. Anywhere after the first few minutes and I should be driving.
 - Version: I have tried versions 0.7.9, 0.7.10, and 0.8.0 with community features both enabled and disabled for each version

title: Fix TSS2 creep issue, no need to send standstill request
body:
TSS2 vehicles don't need for standstill request to be sent. If we send it PCM will go from status 8 to status 11 upon full stop(that where issue is from as we remove standstill request as soon as status != 8). Status 11 is a 3 seconds timer after which PCM goes into state 7 - standstill and asks to press resume or accelerator. After PCM is entered state 7 - standstill_req = False will not switch it back to cruise (8).

Was tested on Corolla TSS2 and Corolla Hybrid TSS2

Associated discussions: #2508 , #1270 , #2473

GM: Fix to allow brakes to release on resume press
body:
**Description**
Fixes issue where GM vehicles can't resume from a stop by pressing the resume button.

A previous PR better matched the OEM brake mode transitions, however it created a regression.

Once mode 0xd (at full stop) has been entered, even sending a request for 0 brakes will not cause the brakes to be released.

This change updates the logic such that when a request for 0 brakes is sent, the mode is forced to mode 0x1. Which allows the brakes to release on resume press.

**Verification**
In the stopped state, verified the resume on button press functions as expected.

title: Implement a Low Voltage Disconnect in next generation hardware (stranded/dead battery fix)
body:
**What are we trying to solve?**
https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/issues/2677

An edge case exists where OP software can boot/crash/freeze to a bad state where the phone's backlight is on while the screen is black (or any other condition where OP doesn't cleanly exit/shutdown). I've personally had at least two events where I was stranded due to this, one while camping (and it only took 6-8 hours for my Prius's tiny battery to drain).

Lead-acid batteries will reduce their usable lifespan if drained past 50% depth of discharge by up to half, and especially considering starting batteries are even more vulnerable (non"deep-cycle"). At 10~ total discharges due to issues with OP over the last year, my Prius's battery is now in need of (costly) replacement.

Consider at even 173mA, a brand new Prius/Prime 12v battery will be at 50% charge after just 5.5 days, something the battery is not designed for (more calculations in above issue)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7257172/101217581-9c728800-364f-11eb-989d-355d8f70104d.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7257172/101220516-ccbc2580-3653-11eb-841a-9f1bf0efa5a6.png)


**Ideas to resolve**
Implement a LVD in comma power to switch off power at 11.7 volts; for example, or even further upstream in Uno. Next generation hardware should have some sort of native implementation, especially for consumer release (software will always eventually crash).

**Immediate fixes**
I've installed one of these https://www.amazon.com/PriorityStart-12-Volt-Pro-SP-Automatic-Battery-Protector/dp/B0030A10V0/ref=sr_1_3?dchild=1&keywords=Priority+Start+12-Volt&qid=1606925871&sr=8-3 - same concept (no, I'm not affiliated with them in any way)

title: comma pedal: acceleration overshoot behind a stopped car
body:
**Describe the bug**

After my car almost came to a complete stop behind another stopped car, openpilot decided to unnecessarily accelerate causing me to manually brake. 

**How to reproduce or log data**

Was driving close to 50 mph following another car, and a red light caused the cars to stop in front of me. My car also braked, but the braking started relatively late, which cause the first forward collision warning.  Ultimately, my car did seem to brake just in time for a smooth stop, but right before reaching 0mph, it randomly decided to accelerate with no movement from the car in front of me. This caused another forward collision warning before I manually braked.

One thing that maybe is relavent is that because of the late braking, I did feel as if my car stopped (or got near stopping) closer behind the car in front of me than it probably would have normally. 

**Expected behavior**

My car should have come to a complete stop, and only accelerate once  the lead car started to move again.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: Eon Gold with black panda
 - Dongle ID: 23b69975490100e4

title: Restarting the comma2 with vehicle running causes dash error which only clears up after vehicle restart
body:
**Describe the bug**

On the Hyundai Genesis 2015-16, when the comma2 starts up the LKAS fault occurs followed by SCC not present then the AEB faults permanently. The AEB fault needs a vehicle restart to clear. 

Other observed behavior:
* The vehicle is fine if the comma to is just shutdown and it is also fine when the device is disconnected from USB(after shutdown). The issue is only present when the comma2 starts and the vehicle is already running.
* During the comma2 restart, I assume there a brief moment when the relay cuts out which is not allowing the cam messages to pass through which trickles down to AEB faulting permanently. 

**How to reproduce or log data**

Restart the comma 2 which the car running

**Expected behavior**

No faults on the dash

title: Long control on Nidec
body:
Long control leads to more disengagement 

Honda Civic 2016 Nidec 

Openpilot has come along way in lateral control. long control leaves something to the desire. This is an argument to shorten the following distance to enhance Saftey. 

I’ve noticed that long control loses the lead car because the distance so far that I can’t track around curves as well and as such in losing and regaining vision of the lead car loan control his poor performance. This leads to further disengagement’s.
 secondlyI noticed that I have to disengage whenever a car pulls in front of me Because open pilot falls back so quickly that other cars make aggressive decisions around my car. Even if I disengage and reset it to see if following distance openpilot again slows down creating a pattern of erratic long control. In this instance you are also increasing disengagements. 

Please consider shortening follow distance Nidec Hondas to reduce these disengagements. Or at least please try a kegmans branch on 1 and 2 bar follow distance on your civic. I have consistently had less disengagement using those following distances and felt the overall drive is safer then your base follow distance, as the the car is more interpretable to other drivers on the road and more predictable to the traffic pattern.

title: 2020 Ioniq EV safety issue
body:
TLDR: 32mph warning displays, blocking out other warnings and displays, but car can steer below 32.

When driving @40mph or lower, the device displays a warning "Cannot steer below 32mph" which takes up most of the screen. When this is active, no other safety warnings can display over it, potentially AEB warnings in extreme cases. I put in a PR including this, but it never went through. The 2020 Ioniq (ev anyway) is capable of driving below 32mph with steering, all the way down to zero, so I'm not sure why this warning even shows up

 * New driving model: fully 3D and improved cut-in detection

 * Grey panda is no longer supported, upgrade to comma two or black panda
 * Lexus NX 2018 support thanks to matt12eagles!
 * Kia Niro EV 2020 support thanks to nickn17!
 * Toyota Prius 2021 support thanks to rav4kumar!
 * Improved lane positioning with uncertain lanelines, wide lanes and exits
 * Improved lateral control for Prius and Subaru

title: Prerotate dmonitoringmodeld input
body:
This should fix the cache issues for good.

https://chromium.googlesource.com/libyuv/libyuv/+/HEAD/docs/rotation.md uses an 8x8 kernel, the proper way to rotate.

Despite having an extra buffer, this actually reduces runtime. I do not expect it to be variable anymore.

Also fixes a bug in input order!

title: Driving Model Request: Segmentation for Semi-Trucks or other Long Body/Cargo Vehicles
body:
The current longitude control of Comma has a follow distance that is mostly acceptable in given situations but the follow distance for large semi trucks puts the vehicle in the truck driver's blind spot. When following a semi truck I, as the driver using OpenPilot perfectly center in the lane, cannot see the side mirrors of the truck therefore the trucks driver is more than likely unable to see me. Riding in the blind spot of any vehicle is dangerous, and this danger is amplified when large trucks are involved at speed.

Suggestion: The model should be able to recognize large-vehicles (like trucks), and set a follow distance such that the side mirrors of the lead large-vehicle are visible to Comma.

title: Lexus IS fails fingerprinting
body:
Lexus IS fails to be detected by open pilot

 `car bug`

** Reproduce bug **

Plug comma2 on master-ci branch. Car is not detected and runs in dashcam-only mode.

**Expected behavior**

We expect the car to be detected and OP to be available for engagement.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
- Device: comma2
- Dongle ID: 268f0090ec7ae6a7
- Route: 268f0090ec7ae6a7|2020-11-16--08-32-58
- Timestamp: 2020-11-16 8:32am EST
- Version: 0.8.0 master-ci branch
- Car make/model: 2018 Lexus IS 350 F Sport

**Additional context**

It appears the addition of the 2017 Lexus IS git commit (`dc819a3df138f3dc39f81489d5bd539901eaf960`)
has led to a regression.

I temporarily fixed the detection by removing the following: 

```
root@localhost:/data/openpilot$ git diff
diff --git a/selfdrive/car/toyota/values.py b/selfdrive/car/toyota/values.py
index a352fa08..1c054b41 100644
--- a/selfdrive/car/toyota/values.py
+++ b/selfdrive/car/toyota/values.py
@@ -748,13 +748,6 @@ FW_VERSIONS = {
       b'\x018966353R1100\x00\x00\x00\x00',
       b'\x018966353R8100\x00\x00\x00\x00',
     ],
-    (Ecu.engine, 0x7e0, None): [
-      b'\x02353P7000\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00530J5000\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00',
-    ],
-    (Ecu.esp, 0x7b0, None): [
-      b'F152653330\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00',
-      b'F152653301\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00',
-    ],
     (Ecu.dsu, 0x791, None): [
       b'881515306400\x00\x00\x00\x00',
       b'881515306500\x00\x00\x00\x00',
```


Also the Ecu.esp section does not show up consistently in the carFw output, so the car or OP needs to be restarted several times in order for OP to recognize the vehicle prior to this regression where the car is not detected at all.

See:  2020-11-15--20-10-20--0 (does not have ecu = esp) vs 2020-11-16--08-32-58--0 ( has ecu=esp)

```
    carFw = [
      ( ecu = esp,
        fwVersion = "F152653330\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00",
        address = 1968,
        subAddress = 0 ),
      ( ecu = dsu,
        fwVersion = "881515306400\x00\x00\x00\x00",
        address = 1937,
        subAddress = 0 ),
      ( ecu = eps,
        fwVersion = "8965B53280\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00",
        address = 1953,
        subAddress = 0 ),
      ( ecu = engine,
        fwVersion = "\x018966353R1100\x00\x00\x00\x00",
        address = 1792,
        subAddress = 0 ),
      ( ecu = fwdRadar,
        fwVersion = "8821F4702300\x00\x00\x00\x00",

        subAddress = 15 ),
      ( ecu = fwdCamera,

```

This wiki page contains a decent amount of information which isn't present in the /tools/sim/README.md document.

title: 2018 Lexus IS 350 F Sport - mid drive CAN Error
body:
**OP Disengages mid-drive with CAN Error and loud beeping**

During an openpilot controlled drive, one of several failure scenarios occurs:

* OP shows CAN Error: check connections + loud triple beeping
* OP triple beeps then goes to status screen showing miles driven, comma points, etc.
* OP triple beeps, then reboots to being functional again
* OP triple beeps, then reboots to not recognizing vehicle.

**log data**

Reproduction steps is to drive a while, then failures occur.

2020-11-13 around 6:15p EST - triple beeped, then went to status screen. OP did not recognize car after restarting vehicle.

2020-11-14 around 1:24p EST - triple beeped, then went to status screen.

2020-11-14 around 3:36p EST - triple beeped, then displayed CAN Error: check connections.

**Expected behavior**

Doesn’t disengage and continues to operate.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: comma2
 - Dongle ID: 268f0090ec7ae6a7
 - Route: 268f0090ec7ae6a7|2020-11-14--15-21-15
 - Timestamp: 2020-11-14 3:36pm EST
 - Version: 0.8.0 master-ci branch
 - Car make/model: 2018 Lexus IS 350 F Sport

**Additional context**

* if it’s a hardware issue, bumpy roads seem to affect error rates a bit.
* seems to run well on smooth highways for 10-30 min stretches before failing
* replacement harness box seems less reliable than original harness box
* could be related to another user with a 2017 is350 where v1 fingerprinting works for him but v2 fingerprinting does not. Is it possible to lose fingerprinting mid-drive?

title: Feature Request : Sliding Scale for Long, Lat Controls
body:
I would love sliders to fine tune control :

drive a bit more to the right or a bit more to the left.  The Sonata stock centering drives just a touch too far to the right for my taste.

Acceleration curves from very aggressive to very conservative - I want my car to accelerate like a golf cart (aka, very VERY slowly)

Braking curves from very aggressive to very conservative (this is there somewhat with following distance in stock "smart cruise" today).  For my purposes in normal traffic, I always want the car in front of me to be moving away from me, not following at a set distance.  This is obviously not possible in stop and go traffic.

title: Update DM awareness times
body:
- This tunes driver monitoring awareness times, previously 2 seconds were given before the alert made noise, now it's up to 6 seconds (9 seconds originally before change in October).
- Also I moved the `hi_std_alert` to only be reset when red terminal status, it would end up displaying every ~20 seconds causing me to take extra time taking my eyes off the road to see what the device is alerting me of. Having it reset when red should have it displaying only once per drive usually (since we don't need to constantly be reminded of the same issue).

Comma 2 Manuel Power on will not work after 30 hour no drive inactivity
body:
**Describe the bug**  
  Comma 2 can not be manually powered on after Comma2 was automatically powered off when the 30 hours of no new drive inactivity period has lapsed.  Before version 0.7.10 and maybe 0.7.9, Comma 2 could be powered on and rebooted after this 30 hours and after not driving every day.  The time out period was to save car battery drain, as a hybrid its critical as the 12v start battery is not a powerhouse device. Now it does nothing, no buzz, blue light steady blinking from panda, using stock version 0.7.10 with the new neos.  No forks just a "plain Jane" setup and auto installs.

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. Add the `car bug` label for vehicle/brand specific bugs and the `bug` label for all other bugs. -->  
  The car will not boot using the manual power button after auto power off inactivity..  The only way to get it booted is to start the car, this starts a boot from scratch, not from the normal screen shown when ready and running.

**How to reproduce or log data**  ..................
   We need to test of a Comma 2 in a car setup and power supply, with a drive completed, Then park it  for 30 hours or until it indicates "appears offline" from the Comma Prime app.  Tapping the screen would open OP ready screen if its less then the 30 hours.  Using stock 0.7.10, no forks, and then attempt to start Comma2 manually with the power button when Comma2 indicates its fully powered off by the timer.
    It normally did power on and boot with a buzz. Now nothing and this would appears to be a software change or bug as its suppose to boot manually. I think the panda which is always running is not allowing it to boot due to a missing line of software.  Otherwise you need to start the car or it remains off line.   But because of the errors from the car it
![2020-11-05_15-41-22](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/65055060/98314008-008b2900-1f8a-11eb-8ad1-3dae1b3adb43.jpg)
 need to be turned off then restarted



<!-- Steps to reproduce the behavior. -->  
  Time out the inactivity timer which has been said to be 30 hours of no drives or starting the car.  The Comma2 is installed and never removed and has been running for months and no cables are unplugged.  The device is not removed nightly as some users as I garage it.  So they might miss this bug as the reattaching Comma2 will open and boot automatically.

**Expected behavior**  After the 30 hours a push of the Comma 2 power button and Comma 2 did start a boot from power off.

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. -->  As per a discussion with Discord and customer support, they also think it is suppose to boot up.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: [e.g. EON/EON Gold/comma two].... 
   Comma 2

 - Dongle ID: [e.g. 77611a1fac303767, can be found in Settings -> Device -> Dongle ID or my.comma.ai/useradmin]
   e4a16227cff292b5

 - Route: [e.g. 77611a1fac303767|2020-05-11--16-37-07, can be found in my.comma.ai/useradmin]
   after any driver, after a 30 hours of no drive which turn Comma2 off.

 - Timestamp: [When in the route the bug occurs (e.g. 4min 30s into the drive)]
    Any time after 30 hours and  power off of Comma2.
    
 - Version: [commit hash when on a non-release branch, or version number when on devel or release2 (e.g. 0.7.6)]
    possibly started in version 0.7.9 as I drove daily, but this version 0.7.10 with days of no driving, no forks, auto updated by your pushes.  Its worked since I got the device without any problems.  As for operation, Comma2 works as advertised and never had any cable problems or needed to insert them to solve any problems.

 - Car make/model: [e.g. Toyota Prius 2016]
   2020 Prius Prime XLE, un plugged DSU and in version 0.7.9 was when I started to try the unplugged DSU driving.  Unplugged DSU allows full Openpilot and the long (Speed and braking are far smoother).  I want to stay unplugged as its better then Toyota stock which is slow acceleration and hard and jerky braking which is truly their AEB at work.

**Additional context**
   Customer service advised it could be the OBD2 power unit or a plug.  I have a spare power module after its case opened and they sent me a second power module, so both were used.  I ran the 30hour time out power off using both power supplies this past week.  All cables are seated and are checked for firmness and fit.

<!-- Add any other context about the problem here. -->
    This manual booting allowed cars with unplugged  DSU's to avoid the car errors thrown when the car is started before Comma2.  Hence the errors,
"Pre-Collsion System Malfunction", 
"Headlight System Malfunction"
"Lane Departure Alert Malfunction"
These erros do not appear and all systems work if the Comma2 is ready before the car starts, and the reason for this bug report.

Attached a video, not professional showing the problem, and why allowing the Manual boot with the Comma2 power button is a necessary step before car starting for unplugged DSU users.

 Additional results 11-17-2020

It appearing that the programming has been changed. Latest test it shuts down after 10 hours but not 24 or 30.  Also was advised the tapping of the Comma2 screen when its in the screen saving mode was changed to a Comma2 sensor as it now opens by shutting the car door or  tap on the windshield, but more a vibration or movement sensor.  So it appears what ever controls the comma2 power options have been changed.
whoever checks these bugs please advise if this is correct.  Many of use might need the Power button to work rather then pulling the usb plug out then reinserting it.  This change is bad.

title: Make the time from initial wheel touch alert to making noise longer
body:
I just took my first drive with 0.7.10 (since 0.7.7) tonight and since I don't have DM at night I use wheel touch. However with the changes to wheel touch timings in this commit https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/commit/21d4ac1eebba06769f03edf7220ce84bd6ae154d I find myself not being able to catch the alert fast enough so that it *doesn't* make noise. If I'm looking straight at the road, as soon as I notice that the alert to touch the wheel has shown, it's just then turning to orange and starts making noise, possibly waking up anyone else in the car (but is also annoying if it's just you).

Is there any way we can either delay this prompt noise, or revert part of that commit to make the time from initial "touch the wheel" alert to making noise alert its original length? It was perfect before, but now makes driving at night much more annoying. Another annoyance is the orange warning alert that makes noise turns on and off repeatedly if the monitoring model is uncertain, since the orange alert resets the `hi_std_alert_enabled` variable, so it's just in a loop until I touch the wheel, even if I'm looking at the road and the model can see me.

That last thing could be solved by a timeout on how quickly it can show the uncertain alert after orange alert is shown.

title: DM not recognizing chinky eyes at night
body:
**Describe the bug**

DM is not working as expected because it is not recognizing that my eyes are in fact open at night. 

This is most likely due to having chinky eyes, and the model is not trained to recognize them. 

**How to reproduce or log data**

I can verify this because the DM will warn that driver is not paying attention just a few seconds into activating OpenPilot, and if I strain to open my eyes wider, then the warning will go away but come right back without wide eyes.

**Expected behavior**

DM should be able to recognize whether eyes are open or closed, whether or not it is day or night.

**Device/Version information:**
 - Device: comma two
 - Dongle ID: 102110287766742152833
 - Route: 06d00785f52b907a
 - Timestamp: When in the route the bug occurs a few seconds after activating the system
 - Version: 0.7.9
 - Car make/model: Honda Civic Hatchback 2017

**Additional context**

This only occurs during the night. DM works just fine during the day. Not sure if it might be camera resolution or weak IR issue and if it can even be rectified. Just received the comma two and have experienced this right out of the box. Right now, I'm using a webcam cover to disable DM at night; not a great solution.

title: Errors when using cantools with openpilot/opendbc/hyundai_kia_generic.dbc
body:
When I launch cantools with hyundai_kia_generic.dbc:
```
$ cantools monitor -c can0 hyundai_kia_generic.dbc
```

**Errors occure:** 

- error: DBC: "Invalid syntax at line 1568, column 10: "BO_ 1191 >>!<<4a7MFC: 8 XXX""
- error: DBC: "Invalid syntax at line 1604, column 9: "BO_ 870 >>!<<366_EMS: 8 EMS""
- error: DBC: "Invalid syntax at line 1611, column 9: "BO_ 854 >>!<<356: 8 XXX""
- error: The signals CF_LkasDawStatus and CF_Lkas_Daw_USM are overlapping in message LKAS12.

**Solution:**

- For the first three errors, the solution is to rename the message so that they don't start with numbers.
- For the last error, the position of the bits for the above signals should be changed.

title: Bug: face detection stopped working during daylight conditions, works fine at night
body:
About a week ago I started getting frequent errors saying that no face was detected on my C2 when driving during the day. It seems to happen more frequently the brighter it is outside. Night drives work fine as always. It seems that the image preview during the day off the driver-facing camera is overexposed/washed out to the point where all detail in the face is obscured, showing only a bright silhouette. Night drives are unaffected and still work fine. Driving on a sunny day though now causes disengages and alarms every few seconds when using OP unless I pretty violently jerk the wheel immediately every time the error pops up. Light tap like on the stock Honda Sensing doesn't work. IR LED's are always on now in any lighting condition, though I admit I'm not sure if they're supposed to be always on or if previously they only came on at night.

Test drive with issue reproduced and driver-facing camera uploaded: Mon, Oct 26 @ 08:00 to 08:25

**How to reproduce or log data**

Drive during the day, the brighter the more often it occurs.

**Expected behavior**

Prior to this, C2 had the same view of driver. Seat position hasn't changed and C2/rearview mirror position is the same, but face tracking was working perfectly with a very high degree of accuracy.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: Comma2
 - Dongle ID: bc014e9a661d4a5e
 - Route: bc014e9a661d4a5e|2020-10-26--08-00-09
 - Timestamp: Throughout the whole drive about twice a minute
 - Version: 0.7.11
 - Car make/model: 2017 Honda Civic EX sedan
**Additional context**

Since this issue started, I've updated from 7.10 to 7.11, and I did an OS update that I was prompted about. Also, my UI is extremely sluggish on the C2, with time from click to response being about 3-5 seconds. Not sure if it's related. No issues driving though. Attached image is during daylight showing IR emitters on and the overexposed image of driver face.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/72579153/97227863-73d3b480-17ac-11eb-9a71-949e6e376f18.png)

**Describe the bug**

echo -en "1" > /data/params/d/DisableUpdates
I was told that is the way to prevent auto updates, but it does not work.
Comma 2 will shutdown and become unresponsive after the car ignition is turned off, resetting the comma 2 will allow it to sleep and wake upon next using the car, but it will crash again at vehicle power off and won't come back on unless it is reset.

**How to reproduce or log data**
SSH into the Comma 2 and enter the command: echo -en "1" > /data/params/d/DisableUpdates

**Expected behavior**
Comma 2 will wake up the next time the car is used and will not crash every time the car is turned off.

title: Tune feedforward for TSS1 Corolla
body:
This is a smaller change tuning-wise for the Corolla than my other PID PR but still improves steering. I disabled both proportional and integral by setting their gains to 0 and just live tuned feedforward. On the highway I arrived at around 1.25x original `kf` however at lower speeds 1.25x doesn't seem to be enough to maintain torque around tighter curves (20-45 degrees) so I balanced both speeds with 1.4x/`0.000084`. *(maybe we can improve the feedforward equation so one value can work better at all speeds)*

Highway curves are smooth and don't overshoot with this tune with just feedforward, and neither do low speeds. **When I added P and I back I had to lower them as feedforward took over most of the turning torque and high P and I gains were not needed as much.** Retuning kf reduced independence on P and I to maintain torque in curves (now just to error correct). **But I will leave this to another PR, this is to just use an all around better kf value.**

**How I tuned feedforward:** Again I set all gains to 0 except ff. When I approached a curve I moved the wheel to center myself in the curve (simulating the missing PI) and then let go to see if `kf` was enough to keep the angle in the curve. If it didn't I raised `kf` and tried again.

**Previous behavior:** Feedforward was too low causing integral (and p a bit) to be used more to maintain angle in curves, there was definitely some oscillation and led to loss of control in tighter curves.

**New behavior:** Feedforward should now be the main factor driving torque to maintain wheel angle in curves with less oscillation as ff torque is more constant/stable than P/I.

Drives into Double yellow lines on a 2 lane highway
body:
Drives into double yellow lanes

2020 Prius Prime XLE, DSU unplugged, Dynamic cruise engaged. While driving on 2 lane US highways US95 in Nevada the car will move into the double yellow lines to the point of trying to straddle the lines.  Happens during darkness, 2 lanes with the no passing lines on the left.  BUT if I turn off cruise and turn on with a 1.5 second or longer it engages standard criuse without radar or long control with open pilot, just lateral control works.  During standard cruise it did not move into the yellow lines.  When in Dynamic cruise with full OP long and lateral  the car again moved into double yellow lines.

In this video "https://my.comma.ai/e4a16227cff292b5/1602985741199/1602992924316#"
time stamped Oct 17  200330 and Oct 17 201645

I expected it to not drive into the center of the road. Happens only with double yellow lines for no passing.


 - Device: Comma2
 - Dongle ID: e4a16227cff292b5
 - Route: https://my.comma.ai/e4a16227cff292b5/1602985741199/1602992924316
 - Timestamp: Oct 17 200330
                      Oct 17 201630
 - Version: open pilot V0.7.9-Release no forks
 - 2020 Toyota Prius Prime XLE
- Calibration 0.9 down, 0.1 left

This was a return trip from Phoenix, AZ to Reno.  The first leg was mentioned in openpilot -experience after the original trip to Phoenix with all the same problems happened.  Both happened about 8:00 PM PDT in total darkness on the Oct 12 just before Gold Hill NV on a freshly coated and lined section with double yellow lines.  The return trip for the bug report happened Oct 17 just past Mercury, NV leaving a divided highway to 2 lane US95. Others on Discord also have mentioned double yellow line problems in 2 lane US highways and driving into the lines.  Its a hard pull into the lines using opposite resistance on the steering wheel.
Original problem was in the drive "https://my.comma.ai/e4a16227cff292b5/1602556277800/1602561465865#" and was mentioned on 10/14/2020 on Discord openpilot-experience.

title: np.matrix is no longer recommended and may be removed in the future
body:
This PR changes all active `np.matrix` variables to `np.array` in `latcontrol_indi.py` ([np.matrix docs message about deprecation](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.matrix.html)). Since the arrays are all no larger than 2D, no change in output should occur.

Here's the comparison of the dot products of K and C both as matrices and as arrays:

```python
>>> np.allclose(np.dot(K, C), np.dot(np.array(K), np.array(C)))
True
```

body:
**Describe the bug**
I cloned the latest code and tried to run openpilot. using ubuntu.
When I execute scons web_camera=1, I produce an err that can be easily solved twice.
The first is the deprecation of the clCreateCommandQueue function in opencl.
One is that there is no err variable.
<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. Add the `simulation` label if running in an environment like CARLA. -->

**How to reproduce or log data**
selfdrive/camerad/main.cc:194:24: error: 'clCreateCommandQueue' is deprecated
      [-Werror,-Wdeprecated-declarations]
  cl_command_queue q = clCreateCommandQueue(s->context, s->device_id, 0, &err);
                       ^
/usr/include/CL/cl.h:1446:72: note: 'clCreateCommandQueue' has been explicitly
      marked deprecated here
  ...cl_int *                       /* errcode_ret */) CL_EXT_SUFFIX__VERSION...
                                                       ^
/usr/include/CL/cl_platform.h:119:74: note: expanded from macro
      'CL_EXT_SUFFIX__VERSION_1_2_DEPRECATED'
  ...#define CL_EXT_SUFFIX__VERSION_1_2_DEPRECATED __attribute__((deprecated))
                                                                  ^
1 error generated.

and

selfdrive/camerad/cameras/camera_webcam.cc:247:7: error: unused variable 'err'
      [-Werror,-Wunused-variable]
  int err;
      ^
selfdrive/camerad/cameras/camera_webcam.cc:265:3: error: use of undeclared
      identifier 'err'
  err = pthread_create(&rear_thread_handle, NULL,
  ^
selfdrive/camerad/cameras/camera_webcam.cc:267:10: error: use of undeclared
      identifier 'err'
  assert(err == 0);
         ^
selfdrive/camerad/cameras/camera_webcam.cc:271:3: error: use of undeclared
      identifier 'err'

title: make hyundai resume reliable
body:
fixes #2142

I found that sending 100 resume commands all at once gives 100% reliability accepting first attempt to resume by spamming resume button over 10+ minutes

sending 100 resume commands all at once might not be a good idea due to the amount of time it takes to send them (since nothing with a higher CAN addr can send messages during that time) so I send 25 every 0.1 seconds

before this change I can sit behind a parked car for less than a minute and have a resume command not be accepted in less than a second (sometimes it will even take 10+ seconds before a resume command is accepted)

after this change I can sit behind a parked car for more than 10 minutes and the longest I saw it take to accept a resume command was 3 attempts (0.3 seconds)

title: [Toyota][Enhancement] Yellow "Hold Steering Wheel" warning on Toyota MFD / HUD
body:
Hi,

When the driver lets go of the steering wheel while using Toyota's factory LKA system, the system initially displays a white "Hold Steering Wheel" warning on the MFD / Dash; if the driver failed to respond, the system will proceed to display another yellow coloured "Hold Steering Wheel" warning on both the MFD / Dash and the HUD to alert the driver.

I am think that this can be used by openpilot to warn users about scenarios that would require an immediate input.

For example:
1. When the turn exceeds the steering limit but the driver failed to respond for a set amount of time
2. When the driver monitoring distraction level reaches promptDriverDistracted
3. When the system disengages unexpectedly

Unfortunately I am unable to find an image that matches my description but this warning does exist. I can try to take a photo of it some day if I think it is safe to do so.

title: Poor Performance with Black Lane Markers
body:
**Describe the bug**
Lines on the highway are painted black (seem to be painted over) but lane reflectors are still present, and seem to have enough contrast that I and other drivers can tell where lane markers are . When Comma is activated it does not see lane markers and will sometimes ride over the lines or get very close to the lane marker it does not see.
<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. Add the `car bug` label for vehicle/brand specific bugs and the `bug` label for all other bugs. -->

**How to reproduce or log data**
Driving South Bound on Hwy 101 from Morgan Hill, CA to Gilroy, CA will reproduce this consistently. 
<!-- Steps to reproduce the behavior. -->

**Expected behavior**
If I and all other drivers can see the lane dividers then Comma should also "see" the lane markers too, so that my vehicle can stay centered in the lane and not begin to ride over the line.

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. -->

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: Comma Two
 - Dongle ID :bdad50b8a1f9fa8e
 - Route: bdad50b8a1f9fa8e|2020-09-20--12-01-31
 - Timestamp: Around 35mins into the drive.
 - Version: v0.7.9 master-ci 9fe3d286a641a23431f4487c8a5980be4d8de4bc
 - Car make/model: 2020 Toyota Rav4 Hybrid LE

**Additional context**

![black-lane-markers](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/70859798/93734286-7b8cb180-fb8d-11ea-8d96-0812533e2824.PNG)

title: Improve realtime performance on NEOS
body:
After reproducing the boardd missed cycles while running ftrace, it seems the CPU 3 jitter is caused by unbound kernel workers doing work that disables preemption being scheduled onto CPU 3 between boardd cycles. Fixing `set_core_affinity` reduces the likelihood of boardd missed cycles since CPU 3 now spends at least 75% of its time in realtime processes.

We still need a way to shield CPU 3 from dynamically created unbound kworkers. Newer kernels expose a config option to do this in sysfs, `/sys/devices/virtual/workqueue/cpumask`.

As a test since the NEOS kernel doesn't have this option, a small waste process running as SCHED_FIFO with minimum realtime priority and pinned to CPU 3 prevents any boardd missed cycles. Boardd and controlsd will preempt the waste process, but the SCHED_OTHER kworker can't get scheduled onto CPU3.

title: Hyundai SCC automatic resume is unreliable
body:
**Describe the bug**

Somewhere in the range of 1% to 10% of the time the car will not accept the resume command from openpilot for 5+ seconds

**How to reproduce or log data**

Sit behind a parked car, engage, and let openpilot send the resume command repeatedly when the car goes into the state where it says press pedal or accel button to resume.

**Expected behavior**

The car always accepts the resume command from openpilot within a second and goes back into the state where it is prepared to accelerate immediately when the lead vehicle pulls away.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Route: You should be able to easily reproduce this issue, if not I can record and provide a route
 - Timestamp: n/a
 - Version: 01111b3f28c748769db8f27646d9086f00a417ef
 - Car make/model: 2020 Hyundai Palisade

**Additional context**

https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/blob/e8c8e9dab25c81fbeefa4fa05bf38166f9abe203/selfdrive/car/hyundai/carcontroller.py#L79-L80

Most of the time the car will accept the very first resume command openpilot sends, but some percentage of the time it takes way too long and you have to manually resume.

What I have tried:
- making the parity bit always correct, and always incorrect and neither seemed to change the reliability (so it seems like the parity bit doesn't matter)
- making the counter always the last counter + 1, sending 15 messages all at once incrementing the counter for each message (so it wraps around back to the next value the car would send) and always sending the counter - 1 which should always be incorrect and nothing seemed to change the reliability (so it seems like the counter doesn't matter)
- increasing the frequency all the way up to 100 Hz, which causes the car to fault and engage the parking break sometimes, and it seems like the higher you increase the frequency the less reliable it becomes

The vehicle sends the button state at 50 Hz so perhaps sometimes the next message from the vehicle will come in very close after openpilot sent a message, overriding what openpilot sent?

I would guess this is an issue for the Sonata and Palisade since they use the same radar and this is related to SCC, and perhaps other vehicles, too.

title: Hyundai SCC standstill resume logic
body:
The current implementation of cruise standstill resume logic is not good enough! There is a constant hit resume display on cluster, and constant cycling until the vehicle start to move. Also the frequency to send clu11 is unnecessary. we can send the clu11 msg at the loop rate the logic is running.

This should have no effect on stock openpilot

title: 2021 Rav4 Prime gets CAN Error even after the fingerprint is added (STEERING_LKA and PRE_COLLISION seems to have a different checksum scheme?)
body:
**Describe the bug**

2021 Rav4 Prime gets CAN Error even [after the fingerprint is added](https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/pull/2018). 

[We've checked the setup against another Rav4 and the harness and C2 do not show the same error message and believe the hardware to be sound.](https://discordapp.com/channels/469524606043160576/524327905937850394/749377789723148368)

We get this error:

![](https://media.discordapp.net/attachments/524327905937850394/748711512910069788/FQpE1sjDSO17Yy-SrAZ68cQiSZd-oakrEjM6gqwBML7pQIa3EmaBIKIft8pEGfu9mtpLqI_c6ULaw2OxssZq0MrZoWvS6rwgzwyY.png)

**How to reproduce or log data**

With a known-good Harness + C2 setup installed in the Rav4 Prime, checkout this branch on the C2: https://github.com/nelsonjchen/openpilot/tree/rav4_prime_fw @ commit 640ae8b

Start the Rav4 Prime.

**Expected behavior**

No CAN Error or `CHECKSUM FAIL` error in `tmux`.

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: Comma 2
 - Dongle ID: 54bb533aec9ff844
 - Route: 54bb533aec9ff844\|2020-08-29--13-31-50
 - Timestamp: 158433520979974 from logs is when the error message is printed to the screen.
 - Version: https://github.com/nelsonjchen/openpilot/tree/rav4_prime_fw @ 640ae8b0b56a52a4eef662192967546e660c66a0
 - Car make/model: 2021 RAV4 Prime (VIN ends in 002147) 

**Additional context**

I've been helping matty#8553 on Discord add support for his 2021 Rav4 Prime to openpilot. Many others and I thought this was as simple as adding the [fingerprint for the TSS2 Rav4 Prime to OP](https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/pull/2018). This turns out to not be the case. 

After reproduction, we have SSH'd into the C2 and taken a look at `tmux a`, we see `CHECKSUM FAIL` spam:

![](https://media.discordapp.net/attachments/524327905937850394/749388683123097740/Screen_Shot_2020-08-29_at_3.02.57_PM.png?width=1237&height=911)

Looking at Cabana, it seems that `STEERING_LKA` is now 8 bytes in size up from 5 bytes in the past and that PRE_COLLISION IS size 8 up from 7.

I took a look at `STEERING_LKA` and tried the existing checksum algorithm [in a scratch-program, I implemented Toyota's checksum per the IOActive document to the last value and seeing if that pre-existing approach works for the RAV4 Prime's 8 byte `STEERING_LKA`. My unit tests work for my Corolla 2020's data. It doesn't for the 2021 Rav4 Prime's data and they don't match.](https://github.com/nelsonjchen/toyota_checksum_2020_scratch/blob/8422bd3b4b7770391e940d31202b8129fdebcb02/src/lib.rs#L97-L108)

The last four bytes for `STEERING_LKA` are rapidly changing. 

![high_entropy](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5363/91650158-ed5f5880-ea30-11ea-9b07-6e3dca7f8f83.gif)

I haven't taken a look at `PRE_COLLISION` other than noticing the size change. Using the existing algorithm on a value here doesn't seem to work either.

Unfortunately, I've hit the limits of what I can do right now. I think Toyota has changed the checksum scheme or something for `STEERING_LKA` and `PRE_COLLISION`. 

I am not the owner of this 2021 Rav4 Prime, matty#8553 on Discord is. 

Please reach out to matty#8553 if you need him to perform some diagnosis. If there may be something out of his depth and Comma staff or someone from the community is not available or willing to help him through the "boring" diagnosis parts such as setup/SSH/forks/etc, let me know and I will be happy to help walk matty#8553 through those tasks.

title: Tune TSS1 Corolla + add derivative for better control
body:
**Description** Added derivative to pid.py for better lateral control. I've added a tune for my 2017 TSS1 Corolla and set all other cars to 0, rendering no change in control. The steering feels much more solid with derivative added, and it loses control *much* less often in tight corners and with curves requiring quick response. It also almost completely removes oscillation on slight curves when the curve is easing back into a straight.

I can provide some routes or data comparing the change, just let me know!

[A change to cereal is also required, here's that PR](https://github.com/commaai/cereal/pull/83)

title: Alert that I need to immediately connect to the internet to check for updates, while connected
body:
**Describe the bug**

Every time I plug in my comma two, after I stop driving, I get an alert, “Inmediately connect to the internet to check for updates. If you do not connect to the internet, openpilot won’t engage in 0 days”. I am connected to the internet (Sidebar says vehicle online), with 4 dots of cell signal, and via WiFi. It used to be a red warning banner, now it’s blue. 

**How to reproduce or log data**

Happens every time I run OpenPilot. 

**Expected behavior**

It should update?

**Device/Version information (please complete the following information):**
 - Device: comma two
 - Dongle ID: f9377828aaadd35e
 - Route: Every route
 - Timestamp: the end of every drive
 - Version: v0.7.7-release
 - Car make/model: 2020 Toyota Corolla

**Additional context**

This is probably a duplicate of one of the later instances of #1004, but the suggestions short of reinstalling openpilot don’t work, and, well, I can’t figure out how to reinstall it from any documentation I’ve found.

title: Kilometers per hour now displayed as km/h
body:
Fixes #2031

Signed-off-by: Christopher Rabotin <christopher.rabotin@gmail.com>

**Description** [#2031](https://github.com/commaai/openpilot/issues/2031) -- Openpilot UI was showing "kph" instead of the correct abbreviation "km/h"

**Verification** -- Searched for the string "kph" in the codebase and replaced it with "km/h" in `paint.cc` and `events.py`. Code and comments still use the Americanized "kph."

title: Kilometers per hour should be "km/h" not "kph"
body: All cars use the correct SI unit "km/h" not the Americanized "kph." Openpilot should do the same.
